{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17566922","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17566922"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T23:51:02+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T23:51:02+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"18904"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"18904","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/18904"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.74,0.05,0.01,0.12,0.09]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"11637"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"80121"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"11637","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/11637"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"18904"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"65398"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"17"},{"type":"tags","id":"18"},{"type":"tags","id":"67"},{"type":"tags","id":"71"},{"type":"tags","id":"76"},{"type":"tags","id":"5678"},{"type":"tags","id":"11260"},{"type":"tags","id":"11349"},{"type":"tags","id":"11352"},{"type":"tags","id":"12867"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"27375"},{"type":"contributions","id":"27376"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"80121","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/80121"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA junior doctor takes a clinical photograph of an interesting skin rash on their patient\u0027s arm during a consultation. The patient provides verbal consent for the photograph to be used for teaching purposes. The doctor is part of a private Facebook group for medical professionals where interesting cases are discussed.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most appropriate action regarding sharing this clinical image?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Share the image after obtaining written consent and removing identifiers","Share the image in the Facebook group with clinical details removed","Share the image immediately as verbal consent was obtained","Share the image after blurring identifying features","Share the image but restrict viewing to medical professionals only"],"correctOptions":[0],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThe most appropriate action is to \u003Cstrong\u003Eshare the image after obtaining written consent and removing identifiers\u003C/strong\u003E. Even with de-identified images, written informed consent must be obtained that specifically outlines how and where the image will be used.\u003C/p\u003E        \u003Cp\u003EThe incorrect options can be explained:\u003C/p\u003E        \u003Cul\u003E        \u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EShare the image in the Facebook group with clinical details removed\u003C/strong\u003E - Social media platforms, even in private groups, are not secure platforms for sharing patient information or images\u003C/li\u003E                \u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EShare the image immediately as verbal consent was obtained\u003C/strong\u003E - Verbal consent is insufficient for sharing clinical images. Written consent specifying the intended use is required\u003C/li\u003E                \u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EShare the image but restrict viewing to medical professionals only\u003C/strong\u003E - Restricting viewing does not overcome the fundamental issues with sharing patient information on social media platforms\u003C/li\u003E                \u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EShare the image after blurring identifying features\u003C/strong\u003E - Simply removing identifiers without proper written consent is insufficient\u003C/li\u003E    \u003C/ul\u003E        \u003Cp\u003EHealthcare professionals must maintain patient confidentiality across all platforms. Clinical images should only be shared through secure, institution-approved channels with appropriate consent and documentation.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Healthcare professionals must never share identifiable patient information on social media platforms, even in closed professional groups.","De-identified clinical images or cases may only be shared with explicit patient consent for educational purposes.","Personal social media accounts should maintain strict professional boundaries with patients."],"references":["Medical Board of Australia. Good medical practice: a code of conduct for doctors in Australia [online]. 2020 [Cited 2025 Jan 15]. Available at: https://www.medicalboard.gov.au/codes-guidelines-policies/code-of-conduct.aspx","Girardi A, Singh NP, Boyd CJ. Using Social Media in Health Care Research Should Proceed With Caution. Comment on \u0022The Use of Social Media for Health Research Purposes: Scoping Review\u0022. J Med Internet Res. 2022 Jan 28;24(1):e35286. doi: 10.2196/35286. PMID: 35089149; PMCID: PMC8838568. Available from: https://pmc.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/articles/PMC8838568/"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"65398"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"18904"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"65398","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/65398"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-01-17T13:17:33+10:30","updatedAt":"2025-01-17T13:18:14+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"11637"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"80121"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"17","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/17"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83d\ude07","name":"Bioethics","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relation